post_text: We are pleased to announce that Family Health Care is working with us to provide medical care for our students and staff. We have school nurses in place at all of our schools and we also have Nurse Practitioner Brittany Slone who has an office at Whitley County Middle School. Although we have not started in person classes, she is available to see any of our students who need to be seen by a medical professional. She is currently taking walk-ins but you can call the middle school at 549-7050 if you would like to make an appointment. While we hope you never need it, rapid tests for COVID-19 are also available at the clinic.

post_text: In an effort to keep our school family and community informed, we want to share that the Whitley County Health Department has advised us that we have a student-athlete from our high school football team who has tested positive for COVID-19. The health department is in the process of conducting contact tracing. If you are a parent/guardian of a high school football player and the health department feels that you need to be concerned about your child, they will contact you during contact tracing. Our custodial staff is disinfecting all areas used by our football team for practice.

Student Online Registration...

The Whitley County School District is excited to announce the addition of Online Registration for our students. Online registration will give parents and guardians the ability to register their child online in a streamlined method. If you are interested in using Online Registration for your child, please visit: https://www.whitley.kyschools.us/Content2/464.

You can also call your child’s school or the Whitley County Board of Education to make an appointment to come in and register using Online Registration. Paper registration is also available at each school location.

If you have any questions please call Patrick Bowlin or Reta Elson at the Whitley County Board of Education, 606-549-7000.

post_text:
Whitley County High School Interim Principal

Effective July 1, 2020 Rachele Rice will be taking the role of Interim Principal at Whitley County High School. This change comes after Dr. Bob Lawson submitted his resignation earlier in the month so he could take the position of Superintendent of Henderson County Schools. Mrs. Rice was an English teacher at the high school for 12 years and has worked the last 13 years as an assistant principal at WCHS. Applications are currently being accepted for the principal position and a replacement for Dr. Lawson is expected to be announced later in July.
text:
Whitley County High School Interim Principal

Effective July 1, 2020 Rachele Rice will be taking the role of Interim Principal at Whitley County High School. This change comes after Dr. Bob Lawson submitted his resignation earlier in the month so he could take the position of Superintendent of Henderson County Schools. Mrs. Rice was an English teacher at the high school for 12 years and has worked the last 13 years as an assistant principal at WCHS. Applications are currently being accepted for the principal position and a replacement for Dr. Lawson is expected to be announced later in July.

post_text: It is the LAST DAY OF SCHOOL for students in the Whitley County School District. We want to say how grateful we are for all of our students. They bring curiosity, enthusiasm and purpose into our classrooms and give meaning to what we do. We are grateful for our employees. They devote themselves to caring for others and make sacrifices daily to make sure our students get what they need. We are grateful for the way everyone has worked together to make this school year proceed as best it could given our circumstances. We hope all of our students and their families have a fun and safe summer. Everyone stay healthy and we look forward to having you back in our schools next school year!

post_text:
An Important Announcement Concerning the Remainder of the 2019-2020 School Year:

Today, during an online meeting,Governor Beshear requested that all Kentucky schools remain on non-traditional instruction through the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Our last day for students will be Friday, May 8th; therefore, students will receive NTI assignments through May 8th. Principals at each school will convey information concerning how to obtain and return NTI assignments and will be sharing other information concerning the end of the school year as decisions are made. Thank you for understanding that we are in an unprecedented situation and are doing our best to meet the needs of our students as we receive information from Governor Beshear and health officials. Continue to watch our district Facebook page as well as your child's school Facebook page for updates. Principals will also be sending our alert calls in an effort to keep you up to date. Continued wishes for everyone to stay healthy and well!

post_text: Week 2 of NTI is almost complete and we have to brag a little. We have students and parents who are handling it like pros! While we sure do miss our students, we are so proud of the great job you all are doing. Let’s stay with it Whitley!! Keep reading--over 2200 books have been read on myON alone in the last couple of weeks. Stay in touch with your teachers as you work through the NTI assignments. They want to work with you to help you get the most you can while you are learning from home. The weather is getting nice and it is important to stay active too. We want everyone to stay healthy and let’s all pull together to do what needs to be done to defeat this virus so we can get back to school!

Important information for our parents/guardians, employees and students--

Today, Governor Beshear asked all Kentucky Superintendents to request another 10 NTI days in an attempt to stop the spread of COVID-19. This will put our tentative date to return to school at April 20th. More information will follow next week as to how students will be able to get the additional ten days of NTI assignments. We realize this is a stressful and uncertain time, but we appreciate your understanding as we continue to do our best to meet the needs of our students and employees and to also be responsive to the efforts to prevent sickness in our community.

Attention Parents and Students:
Jason Lindsey with Hooked on Science has free science resources available at www.hookedonscience.org. A link to this website can be found under Student Links on the Whitley County School District Webpage. The site offers free resources for parents and students in grades Kindergarten through Fifth. These resources include an archive of experiments, experiment guides, science games, and free weekly videos. The weekly videos can be found under the “Science on the Go” link at the top of the page written in orange and black. The experiment archives and experiment guides can be found under the “Experiment Archive” link in orange. The free science games can be found under the “Quick Links.”

These tests WILL count toward the student's exit criteria as bonus points. Please click or tap on image for instructions.

post_text: Good Morning Whitley County Schools Family! We know the students are working from home for now, but we want everyone to know that we have folks who are hard at work making sure our students are going to be returning to sanitized schools. Our custodians are wiping down frequently touched surfaces with bleach and water and our maintenance department is spraying with a chemical that kills coronavirus and is suggested for use during the COVID- 19 outbreak. We look forward to seeing our students when Governor Beshear announces it is safe for them to return. Everyone take precautions to stay healthy!

Some Oak Grove students and their amazing Impact archery team competed this weekend in the KY State Indoor Tournament. Paisley McKiddy scored a new PR of 150 with 21 x’s and came away with first place in elementary female open in the tournament. As a result of her performance at state and the other regional tournaments she brought home Shooter of the Year for Indoor Elementary Female Open.
Braylynn Spray finished in 10th place.
Tanner Logan finished in 5th place.
Mason Partin did outstanding for his first state tournament even with bow issues.
Congratulations to all you!

This is an annual essay contest honoring grandparents across the state and celebrating the importance of grandparents in the lives of children everywhere.

Marcus’s essay will be considered in the next level of competition competing with students across the state. Mrs. Brashear along with the teachers, staff, and students at WCIS want to congratulate Marcus on his award and wish him the best of luck competing at state!

post_text: Appalachian Entrepreneurship Academy opportunity!
shared_text:
SURVEYGIZMO.COM
AEA 2020 - Student Application

Partners for Education at Berea College
February 12 at 9:18 PM ·

Appalachia's high school seniors enrolled in the 2020-2021 school year are invited to apply for the Appalachian Entrepreneurship Academy (AEA), a four-week, all expenses paid, immersive entrepreneurial experience! The academy was founded by the Appalachian Regional Commission and made possible by the Institute for Educational Leadership. Applications are due by March 6, 2020!

Apply:https://www.surveygizmo.com/s3/5400227/ARC-AEA-Student-Application

What is the Appalachian Entrepreneurship Academy?

1. A residential summer program for the next generation of Appalachian innovators and entrepreneurs.
2. An opportunity for skill-building tutorials in business planning, product development, and idea modeling.
3. Paid work experience with businesses, startups, and other members of Appalachia's budding entrepreneurial ecosystem.
4. A chance to win seed funding in a team-based professional pitch competition.

More Information: https://www.arc.gov/program_areas/AppalachianEntrepreneurshipAcademy.asp

Appalachia's high school seniors enrolled in the 2020-2021 school year are invited to apply for the Appalachian Entrepreneurship Academy (AEA), a four-week, all expenses paid, immersive entrepreneurial experience! The academy was founded by the Appalachian Regional Commission and made possible by the Institute for Educational Leadership. Applications are due by March 6, 2020!

Apply:https://www.surveygizmo.com/s3/5400227/ARC-AEA-Student-Application

What is the Appalachian Entrepreneurship Academy?

1. A residential summer program for the next generation of Appalachian innovators and entrepreneurs.
2. An opportunity for skill-building tutorials in business planning, product development, and idea modeling.
3. Paid work experience with businesses, startups, and other members of Appalachia's budding entrepreneurial ecosystem.
4. A chance to win seed funding in a team-based professional pitch competition.

More Information: https://www.arc.gov/program_areas/AppalachianEntrepreneurshipAcademy.asp

Whitley County Kindergarten Readiness added 66 new photos to the album: Shapes.
January 24 at 2:04 PM ·

This week our Play & Learn Groups focused on shapes. Learning to recognize shapes is an important step on the way to learning to recognize letters. When children learn about shapes they are not only building skills that will help them with reading but also with writing, and math.

We are very thankful to have such a wonderful group of parents, grandparents and caregivers that are so involved in the lives of these children and dedicated to bringing them to our play and learn groups each week.

Invite someone you know that cares for a child ages 3-5 to come and be a part of our efforts to increase kindergarten readiness each week at a location that works best for you. We would love to see you there! 🙂🐻📚🖍️

shared_text:
David Sweet‎Whitley Co. High School Drama
December 14, 2019 at 11:55 AM ·

Tonight is the last night for A Christmas Story! Curtain at 7pm. Admission $5

So blessed to have such a wonderful Director in Melissa Gail Satterfield Woods. She has done such an incredible job with these young actors and has allowed me to take a back seat as technical director with this show at a time when I needed a different focus.

This young cast is wonderful. Many have stepped up for their first show or first major roles. I am looking forward to the future for Colonel Players.

We are blessed to have such great support from our community, school family, WCHS administrators, maintenance staff, and Board of Education. This show features our new stage, some new lights and new curtains and several new actors in the troupe.

We also want to thank Scott Powell for some fantastic photos. We hope you can join us tonight!
